    <title>Combined summary - A summary list of all concerns related to not rising the block size</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T19:18:09.954294+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-August/010188.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The ongoing debate over the block size limit in Bitcoin has raised various concerns and risks for the future of the cryptocurrency. Rising fees are one of the primary issues, with potential indirect consequences and software problems independent of concrete block size that need to be solved. One of the major concerns is that high fees can reduce the utility of people using the network, making some use cases nonviable and discouraging experimentation with new Bitcoin use cases. Moreover, high fees can make Bitcoin more vulnerable to regulation by keeping its user base from growing.There is a fear that increasing fees could lead to the indefinite backlog of transactions, causing people to abandon Bitcoin and migrate to other systems with lower fees. In contrast, increasing the limit also runs the risk of delaying the development of the transaction fee market. The debate over increasing the block size limit in Bitcoin has been ongoing for several years, as proponents argue that it is necessary to prevent constantly full blocks that can cause transaction backlogs.However, others argue that increasing the limit could lead to centralization and undermine Bitcoin's decentralized nature. The decision to increase the block size limit or not will have significant implications for the future of Bitcoin and requires careful consideration and consensus-building among stakeholders. There are also abstract fears associated with Bitcoin's future, including a general fear that something bad will happen when nodes choke up on a backlog of transactions, leading to losses for Bitcoin-based businesses and a potential flight of users to other cryptocurrencies. Other specific concerns include the belief that the exchange rate will decline due to network unreliability and the comparison of Bitcoin to a cargo cult, where believers wait for a range of hoped-for events to occur.One argument against increasing the block size limit is that governments or banking groups could utilize a significant portion of each block's capacity for their settlement network, which would make it difficult for regular users to include transactions. However, during a spam attack, people were still able to send payments without issues by increasing the fee slightly, indicating that bigger blocks do not immediately get filled and create more space for everyone.The block size debate has been a controversial topic in the Bitcoin community for several years. One of the main concerns related to rising fees is that low-fee transactions may become more unreliable, causing people to migrate to competing systems with lower fees. Another concern relates to a software problem independent of block size, where Bitcoin Core's mempool is unbounded in size, making the program crash by using too much memory and there is no good way to increase the fee of a slow transaction. Despite these concerns, Bitcoin has survived and even thrived since this conversation took place. Its exchange rate has fluctuated over the years, but it remains one of the most popular cryptocurrencies in circulation. The ongoing conversation highlights the importance of balancing security and usability in the block size debate. Stakeholders need to carefully consider the long-term implications of any decision regarding the block size limit to ensure the future success of Bitcoin.</summary>
